{{NewZealand-university-stub}}

"'''More Product, Less Process: Revamping Traditional Archival Processing'''" is a 2005 [[archival science]] article written by [[Mark A. Greene]] and [[Dennis Meissner]] that first appeared in the Fall/Winter 2005 issue of ''[[American Archivist|The American Archivist]]''.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|208}} The paper argues that traditional [[archival processing]] is too slow and advocates for the use of minimal processing in order to reduce backlogs and provide access to archival collections as quickly as possible.<ref name=GM>{{cite journal |last=Greene |first=Mark A. |author2=Dennis Meissner |title=More Product, Less Process: Revamping Traditional Archival Processing |journal=[[American Archivist]] |volume=68 |year=2005 |pages=208–263|URL=http://www.archivists.org/prof-education/pre-readings/IMPLP/AA68.2.MeissnerGreene.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|208}} The ideology presented in the article, abbreviated as '''MPLP''',  has since been widely adopted in modern archival theory with subsequent praise directed primarily towards the ability to increase user accessibility without prohibiting the option for future processing.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url=https://medium.com/archives-records/the-pros-and-cons-of-mplp-586b0efc8fba |title=The Pros and Cons of 'MPLP'|last=Mersiovsky|first=Kate |date=2014-12-14|website=Archives & Memory |access-date=2018-04-24 }}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://siarchives.si.edu/blog/how-much-enough|title=How Much is Enough? |date=August 17, 2010 |publisher=Smithsonian Institution Archives|access-date=2018-04-24|last=Wright |first=Jennifer|language=en}}</ref><ref name="Owens" /><ref name="Bromley" /><ref name="Moore" />

== Article summary ==

=== Call to action ===
[[File:Archive boxes.JPG|thumb|Archival storage boxes]]
Greene and Meissner begin the article with a call to action, citing the British report ''[[Best Value and Local Authority Archives]]'', which claims that archival [[cataloging]], arrangement, and description are "not working" and that growing backlogs are "weakening the archival profession".<ref name="GM" />{{rp|208–9}} The authors hypothesize that "processing projects squander scarce resources", and that it is thus necessary to entirely reframe the discussion about processing rather than simply suggesting a new processing technique.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|209}} Their methodology included a [[literature review]], an overview of [[National Historical Publications and Records Commission]] (NHPRC) [[grants]], two [[Survey methodology|surveys]], and examination of other relevant studies.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|209}}

Greene and Meissner discuss what they perceive to be problems with processing and cite a 1998 [[Association of Research Libraries]] (ARL) survey of [[special collections]] units which found that nearly a third of [[manuscript]] collections made up uncatalogued backlogs.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|210}} 

The authors present a new set of guidelines for arrangement, preservation, and description:

# Expediting the availability of collections to users;
# Assuring ''adequate'' arrangement of materials for users' needs;
# Taking the ''minimum ''steps necessary for physically preserving collection materials;
# Describing materials ''sufficiently'' for use.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|212–3}}

=== Major findings ===
The authors argue that arrangement at the [[Fonds|''item'' level]] is not necessary and instead emphasize the importance of creating [[Finding aid|finding aids]] for collections instead.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|214–20}} The authors then discuss the rate at which [[Archivist|archivists]] are able to process collections, citing a 1982 study by [[Karen Temple Lynch]] and [[Thomas E. Lynch]] that put the figure at 12.7 hours per cubic foot.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|223}} Further citing a study by the [[Billy Graham Center|Billy Graham Center Archives]] that found the cost of processing as high as 15.1 hours and $374 per foot,<ref name="GM" />{{rp|225–6}} Greene and Meissner lament that with regard to processing, archivists "have utterly failed to come to grips with a critical administrative reality, a reality that eats 90 percent of our direct program expenditures".<ref name="GM" />{{rp|227}}

The authors propose five major findings from their research:

# Arrangement was still often at the item level;
# Only 51% of repositories were regularly putting [[finding aid|finding aids]] online;
# While most repositories have some preservation considerations, very few do it consistently;
# Repositories were not responding to the challenges presented by backlogs;
# Many of the repositories store their collections in appropriate [[temperature]] and [[relative humidity]] conditions, but still feel the need to remove metal fasteners (which the authors argue is unnecessary).<ref name="GM" />{{rp|230–1}}

=== Principles for change ===
Recognizing that tradeoffs must be made, Greene and Meissner argue that some preservation concerns must be given up for the sake of providing effective access to users of collections.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|236–7}} 

They then present their "principles for change" as recommendations for [[Archivist|archivists]]:

* The Golden Minimum: to reach the processing requirements of current and future users at the most basic level.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|240–1}}
* Arrangement: As opposed to organization of individual items, arranging collections at the [[Fonds|series and folder levels]] simplifies and facilitates research for prospective users.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|241}}
* Description: to embody the materials, provide context and access information to the user, and reflect the level of arrangement.<ref name="GM" />{{rp|245–6}}
* Preservation: Modern climate controlled storage can be trusted to preserve materials following minimalist processing. <ref name="GM" />{{rp|251}}
* Policies: “Unprocessed collections should be presumed open to researchers. Period.”<ref name="GM" />{{rp|252}}
* Metrics: Consistency must be established at the most basic acceptable level among all aspects of [[archival processing]].<ref name="GM" />{{rp|252}}

"More Product, Less Process" concludes that because greater funding and resources are not forthcoming, archivists must "change the way we process so that we can, with our existing resources, roughly triple the speed with which we process".<ref name="GM" />{{rp|254}}  The authors acknowledge the difficulty of their prospective changes, similar issues that [[Librarian|librarians]] face, and the innovative processing work done at institutions including [[Arizona State University]], [[Yale University]], [[Marquette University]], the [[University of Central Florida]], the [[University of Montana]], and the [[Wisconsin Historical Society]].<ref name="GM" />{{rp|255–6}}

== Influence and reception ==
The minimal processing approach advocated by "More Product, Less Process" has been implemented by many archives and [[library|libraries]], including but not limited to the [[Library of Congress]], the [[University of North Carolina]]'s Wilson Library, and the Academic Health Center Archives at the [[University of Minnesota]].<ref name="Owens">{{Cite web|url = http://blogs.loc.gov/digitalpreservation/2012/08/more-product-less-process-for-born-digital-collections-reflections-on-curatecamp-processing/|title = More Product, Less Process for Born-Digital Collections: Reflections on CurateCamp Processing|date = August 22, 2012|accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = The Signal: Digital Preservation|publisher = [[Library of Congress]]|last = Owens|first = Trevor}}</ref><ref name="Bromley">{{Cite web|url = http://amongotheritems.org/2009/11/more-product-less-process/|title = More Product, Less Process|date = November 1, 2009|accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = Among Other Items|publisher = [[WordPress]]|last = Bromley|first = Ben}}</ref><ref name="Moore">{{Cite web|url=http://editions.lib.umn.edu/ahcarchives/2006/10/16/more-product-less-process/|title=More product, less process|last=Moore|first=Erik|date=October 16, 2006|website=Academic Health Center History Project|publisher=[[University of Minnesota]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|accessdate=April 23, 2018}}</ref> Greene and Meissner's article has been highly influential within the archival community, and it has inspired multiple series of presentations, seminars, workshops, and webinars on minimal processing.<ref name=SAA1554>{{Cite web|url = http://saa.archivists.org/events/implementing-more-product-less-process-1554/554/|title = Implementing "More Product, Less Process" #1554|date = |accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = archivists.org|publisher = [[Society of American Archivists]]|last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=TR>{{Cite web|url = http://www2.archivists.org/prof-education/course-catalog/tr-implementing-%E2%80%9Cmore-product-less-process%E2%80%9D|title = [TR] Implementing “More Product, Less Process”|date = |accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = archivists.org|publisher = [[Society of American Archivists]]|last = |first = }}</ref><ref name=Rutgers>{{Cite web|url = http://march.rutgers.edu/2012/03/workshop-more-product-less-process/|title = Workshop: More Product, Less Process|date = March 1, 2012|accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = Mid-Atlantic Regional Center for the Humanities|publisher = [[Rutgers University]]|last = Magnuson-Hung|first = Mandi}}</ref><ref name=PowerPoint>{{Cite web|url = http://www.powershow.com/view2b/460ec0-YmIxM/More_Product_Less_Process_powerpoint_ppt_presentation|title = More Product, Less Process: - PowerPoint PPT Presentation|date = |accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = PowerShow.com|publisher = CrystalGraphics, Inc.|last = Greene|first = Mark A.|last2 = Meissner|first2 = Dennis}}</ref><ref name=ALCTS>{{Cite web|url = http://www.ala.org/alcts/confevents/upcoming/webinar/041112|title = More Product, Less Process: Why It Matters to Archivists, Librarians, and Researchers|date = |accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = [[Association for Library Collections and Technical Services]]|publisher = [[American Library Association]]|last = Meissner|first = Dennis}}</ref><ref name=ALAConnect>{{Cite web|url = http://connect.ala.org/node/163943|title = ALCTS webinar: "More Product, Less Process": Why It Matters to Archivists, Librarians, and Researchers|date = December 23, 2011|accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = ALA Connect|publisher = [[American Library Association]]|last = Spidal|first = Debra}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=alctsce|title=More Product, Less Process: Why It Matters to Archivists, Librarians, and Researchers|date=2012-08-22|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YqftrBsHAl8|accessdate=2018-04-23}}</ref> Emphasis has been drawn towards the argument's devotion to combating extensive backlogs and rethinking [[archival processing]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://library.sc.edu/blogs/scpc/2017/06/23/more-product-less-process/|title=More Product, Less Process: A Reassessment|last=Moore|first=Kate|date=June 23, 2017|website=A Capital Blog|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>  The [[University of South Carolina Library|University of South Carolina' libraries']] blog cites their collection of the papers of Environmentalist, Inc. as a product of MPLP through its lack of thorough processing, but extensive availability to the public.<ref name=":2" /> <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://library.sc.edu/p/Collections/SCPC/collections?Collection=EnvironmentalistsInc|title=South Carolina Political Collections, University Libraries, University of South Carolina|website=library.sc.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref> The article has also inspired the name of "More Podcast, Less Process", an archives-related [[podcast]] hosted by Jefferson Bailey of the [[Metropolitan New York Library Council]] and Joshua Ranger of AudioVisual Preservation Solutions.<ref name=Podcast>{{Cite web|url = http://keepingcollections.org/more-podcast-less-process/|title = More Podcast, Less Process|date = |accessdate = August 26, 2014|website = Keeping Collections|publisher = [[WordPress]]|last = |first = }}</ref>

Prior to Mark Greene's death in 2017,<ref name=":2" /> the authors continued to expand their original thesis, notably in a 2010 ''[[Journal of Archival Organization]]'' article that amplifies their resource allocation argument and directly rebuts a variety of critics.<ref name="jao">{{cite journal|author=Meissner, Dennis and Mark A. Greene|first=|date=|year=2010|title=More Application while Less Appreciation: The Adopters and Antagonists of MPLP|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/15332748.2010.554069|journal=Journal of Archival Organization|volume=8|pages=174–226|doi=10.1080/15332748.2010.554069|via=}}</ref>

Criticism of "More Product, Less Process" has been primarily directed towards its perceived broadness, lenience, and reductive perspective.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last=Phillips|first=Jessica|date=2015|title=A Defense of Preservation in the Age of MPLP|url=https://doi.org/10.17723/0360-9081.78.2.470|journal=The American Archivist|volume=Vol. 78, No. 2|pages=470–487|via=}}</ref> One piece argues MPLP's poor application to item level [[digitization]] and notes the ambiguity of relying on relative importance and condition to determine processing priority.<ref name=":0" /> A 2015 article in ''[[American Archivist|The American Archivist]]'' criticizes MPLP as overtly negative and negligent towards the values of preservation and argues that the philosophy places collections themselves at risk.<ref name=":3" /> Greene  and Meissner's response reiterates their argument and the opportunity cost relationship of processing and user access.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Greene|first=Mark A.|last2=Meissner|first2=Dennis|date=2016|title=To the Editor|url=https://doi.org/10.17723/0360-9081.79.1.219|journal=The American Archivist|volume=Vol. 79, No. 1|pages=219–221|via=}}</ref>
